{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570163"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:38:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:38:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22762"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22762"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.07,0.05,0.5,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112072"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15709"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94138"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45880"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45882"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112072"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of constant upper abdominal pain. She reports no fever, dysuria, urinary frequency, vomiting, bowel change, or vaginal symptoms. Her medical history includes hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her regular medication is perindopril; she uses diclofenac as needed. She lives independently and has not travelled recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Pulse rate 78/min, blood pressure 138/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, temperature 36.7\u00b0C. The abdomen is soft with mild right flank tenderness and no guarding or masses. Bowel sounds are present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn abdomino-pelvic CT is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the radiological findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ovarian cyst","Appendix mass","Small bowel obstruction","Bladder diverticulum","Diverticulitis-associated pericolic abscess"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT abdomen and pelvis shows a 4 cm outpouching arising from the right lateral wall of the urinary bladder (annotated by a triangle in the figure below). Bladder outpouchings or diverticula are relatively common incidental findings on cross-sectional imaging. They reflect focal herniation of the bladder mucosa through the detrusor. On computed tomography, a diverticulum characteristically demonstrates continuity with the bladder lumen and fills with urine or contrast. Correctly identifying pelvic anatomy on imaging prevents misdiagnosis of bowel or gynaecological pathology, particularly in older adults where presentations can be non-specific.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder diverticulum\u003C/strong\u003E is supported by the computed tomography description of a 4 cm contrast-filled outpouching arising from the right lateral bladder wall with clear continuity to the bladder lumen. The absence of adjacent inflammatory stranding, bowel obstruction, or adnexal features further supports a urothelial origin. These lesions are often incidental but can be associated with urinary stasis, stones, infection, or bladder outlet obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian cyst\u003C/strong\u003E would be expected to arise from the adnexa and lie separate from the bladder wall, typically appearing as a thin-walled cystic structure without demonstrable communication with the bladder. The CT show an outpouching continuous with the bladder lumen, arguing against an adnexal cyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAppendix mass\u003C/strong\u003E (phlegmon or abscess) would localise to the right iliac fossa along the caecal pole and typically demonstrates periappendiceal fat stranding, a thickened tubular appendix, or a collection without contrast continuity with the bladder. The observed finding arises from the bladder wall and lacks inflammatory features expected for appendiceal disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E would present with dilated proximal small bowel loops, a transition point, and often air\u2013fluid levels on imaging. A solitary bladder wall outpouching does not fit obstruction, and the patient lacks vomiting, distension, or high-pitched bowel sounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis-associated pericolic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears adjacent to a thickened segment of colon with pericolic fat stranding and possibly extraluminal gas. The lesion described is contiguous with the bladder lumen rather than the colon, and there is no obvious colonic wall thickening or surrounding inflammatory change.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bladder diverticula appear on computed tomography as outpouchings from the bladder wall that often fill with contrast and may be incidental.","Right iliac fossa or flank tenderness in older adults has a broad differential; correlation with imaging anatomy is essential to avoid misattribution to bowel or gynaecological causes.","Incidental bladder diverticula warrant assessment for outlet obstruction and complications such as urinary stasis, stones, or recurrent infection."],"references":["Zhu GG, Siegel CL, Rogers DM, Sagel J, Morrell G, Olpin JD, Schmidt B, Hoegger MJ. Urinary bladder diverticula: imaging features and complications. Abdom Radiol (NY). 2025 Aug;50(8):3584-3598. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39890634/","Bickle I, Fahrenhorst-Jones T, Bell D, et al. Urinary bladder diverticulum. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 24 Aug 2025) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-25906"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22762"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22066"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22070"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22066"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/UHnVh9EHNz1m6aDhqEas5WCE7LuY9U.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/UHnVh9EHNz1m6aDhqEas5WCE7LuY9U.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"media","id":"22070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22070"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Wq7iQJgOlkJojE06rpkqkMxOUvnO5s.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Wq7iQJgOlkJojE06rpkqkMxOUvnO5s.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-24T18:00:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-24T18:01:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15709"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112072"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nu